  "text": "The sensitivity of lysosome/phagosome interactions to Ca 2ϩ suggests that the cytosolic docking and fusion machinery contains one or more Ca 2ϩ -sensing proteins. One candidate is calmodulin, inhibitors of which have previously been shown to interfere with phagosome maturation in vivo [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Analysis of in vitro reaction products shows calmodulin staining in association with both lysosomes and phagosomes ( Figure 8A ) that was dependent on ATP (unpublished data). In Figure 8 , B-F, we studied the effects of different calmodulin inhibitors in the cell-free scintillation proximity assay. Under low Ca 2ϩ reaction conditions, W7, trifluoperazine, and calmidazolium inhibited docking in a concentration-dependent manner (Figure 8, B-D) . W5, a de-chlorinated and less potent analog of W7 [CITATION_6] , was without effect ( Figure 8B ).",
